00:01:45.770 --> 00:01:53.400
Alright so another question we have Alois
is about a forehand problem and the question

00:01:53.400 --> 00:01:57.570
is I can't get the ball on the table while
playing the forehand it always goes long and

00:01:57.570 --> 00:02:01.900
misses the table. What should I do?

00:02:01.900 --> 00:02:07.110
So the natural cure for the ball that is going
long is to put a little bit more topspin on

00:02:07.110 --> 00:02:13.379
the ball so if you're hitting the ball too
flat and too fast then the ball is going to

00:02:13.379 --> 00:02:18.730
tend to go out past the table. If you start
to put just a little bit of topspin on the

00:02:18.730 --> 00:02:25.829
ball then the topspin is going to drag the
ball down onto the table so that's probably

00:02:25.829 --> 00:02:30.620
one of the things that you can look at. The
other thing is also just adjusting the angle

00:02:30.620 --> 00:02:36.219
of your bat so it could be as simple as instead
of your bat being at that angle just turn

00:02:36.219 --> 00:02:40.959
it down and forward a fraction and play the
same stroke that you're playing at the moment

00:02:40.959 --> 00:02:45.450
and maybe that will cure the problem. Always
remember though with your forehand stroke

00:02:45.450 --> 00:02:49.180
to get that bat coming up towards that eyebrow.

00:02:49.180 --> 00:02:58.059
OK. Good advice there. So really topspin is
the key.

